# tridb_fix_double_scan_snapshot.patch — DEV-1236 snapshot-lifetime HARDENING (not the repro crash)
#
# STATUS: applies cleanly (git apply --check exit 0) against vendor/MSVBASE after the prior patches
# (l2_distance_scalar, sptag_optional_build, tridb_vector_index_seam, tridb_vector_iter,
# tridb_tjs_operator) and builds clean via x86build.sh --docker.
#
# IMPORTANT — what this is, honestly: this is latent-UB HARDENING. The SRF operators borrowed
# GetActiveSnapshot() across multi-call SRF re-entry without RegisterSnapshot/PushActiveSnapshot,
# which is incorrect per Postgres snapshot-ownership rules, and topk/multicol_topk teardown had a
# real use-after-free. BOTH are worth fixing. HOWEVER, controlled stock-vs-patched testing did NOT
# reproduce a crash that this patch flips: the operator+own-table-scan plpgsql shape survives with
# AND without this patch. The crash originally filed under DEV-1236 reproduces deterministically as
# the HNSW no-ORDER-BY bug — fixed by tridb_hnsw_scan_no_orderby.patch, NOT this one.
# See docs/fork_segfault_double_scan.md and docs/decisions/0010-fork-operator-snapshot-lifecycle.md.
#
# WHAT IT FIXES (DEV-1236 diagnosis):
#   Co-issuing a second executor-driven scan in the SAME plpgsql block as topk()/multicol_topk()/tjs()
#   crashes the backend (SIGSEGV confirmed on stock image via scripts/smoke_test.sh). Root cause: each
#   operator builds a child IndexScan via SPI and drives it across MULTIPLE SRF per-call invocations
#   using the caller's active snapshot captured ONCE at CreateQueryDesc (GetActiveSnapshot()), never
#   pinned via RegisterSnapshot and never re-pushed. A sibling statement in the same plpgsql block
#   pushes/refreshes the active snapshot (pl_exec.c exec_run_select -> PushActiveSnapshot(...)); after
#   the sibling completes, the active snapshot is potentially displaced. The next ExecProcNode
#   dereferences xs_snapshot (the captured estate snapshot) for MVCC visibility -- if that snapshot was
#   freed by the sibling's pop, this is a read of freed memory -> SIGSEGV. Secondary confirmed defect:
#   topk/multicol_topk teardown has a use-after-free (free(state) then free(state->qDescs) reads state->
#   after free) and mismatched free()/delete for new-allocated std::vectors. tjs_operator.cpp's
#   EndTJSState already had correct teardown order; only the snapshot changes apply to it.
#
# THE FIX (Parts A-D):
#   A: add `Snapshot query_snapshot;` field to FaginsState (topk.cpp, multicol_topk.cpp) and to
#      TJSState (tjs_operator.cpp). Passed through InitFaginsState / InitTJSState.
#   B: at first-call, take `RegisterSnapshot(GetTransactionSnapshot())` instead of `GetActiveSnapshot()`
#      in CreateQueryDesc(...). Stash on state for Parts C and D.
#   C: wrap each child drive (execFagins/execFaginsM/execTJS drain loop) in
#      PushActiveSnapshot(estate->query_snapshot) / PopActiveSnapshot(), with PG_TRY/PG_CATCH/PG_END_TRY
#      to pop on the error path (mirrors core functions.c postquel_getnext pattern).
#   D: teardown -- UnregisterSnapshot(state->query_snapshot) after ExecutorEnd (the last consumer);
#      then fix UAF: delete every new'd member first, free(state) LAST.
#
# PATCH APPLIES TO: vendor/MSVBASE AFTER all prior patches (l2_distance_scalar, sptag_optional_build,
#   tridb_vector_index_seam, tridb_vector_iter, tridb_tjs_operator). The apply order in
#   scripts/lib/msvbase_patches.sh enforces this. Confirmed: cd vendor/MSVBASE &&
#   git apply --check ../../scripts/patches/tridb_fix_double_scan_snapshot.patch -> exit 0.
#
